@page
@model SidebarNavigation.Pages.Docs.GettingStartedModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Getting Started";
}

<section class="hero-card mb-4">
    <h1 class="h3 mb-3">Getting Started with Sidebar Navigation</h1>
    <p class="lead mb-2">
        Start with a stable page hierarchy, then map that hierarchy into sections that are easy to scan on desktop and easy to open on mobile.
    </p>
    <p class="mb-0 text-secondary">
        This page sits inside the <strong>Foundation</strong> section of the sidebar and demonstrates how content and navigation remain aligned.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="feature-grid">
    <article class="content-card">
        <h2 class="h5">Step 1: Group related pages</h2>
        <p class="mb-0">Build sections such as Docs, Products, Blog, and Support before styling the sidebar. Navigation is easier when page groups are clear.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="content-card">
        <h2 class="h5">Step 2: Choose where nesting is useful</h2>
        <p class="mb-0">Use 2 to 3 levels only where the hierarchy is meaningful. In this project, Guides is nested inside Docs to show a deeper structure.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="content-card">
        <h2 class="h5">Step 3: Keep mobile in mind</h2>
        <p class="mb-0">On smaller screens the same sidebar content moves into an offcanvas panel so users do not lose access to the section links.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="content-card">
        <h2 class="h5">Step 4: Highlight context</h2>
        <p class="mb-0">The active page is styled differently, and the current section stays expanded so users can see where they are immediately.</p>
    </article>
</section>
